Academic policy support, jointly funded by our organisation and ARES, delivers research output on specific themes of interest to Belgian development cooperation on demand of the Belgian government. This research output is actively and appropriately spread among various Belgian development actors; not only to government actors, but also to non-governmental actors, the Belgian Development Agency (ENABEL) and the Belgian Investment Company for Developing Countries (BIO). The goal is to improve the relevance and performance of Belgian development cooperation policy with regard to the international framework of sustainable and inclusive development.

Cambodia has regained its place on the partner country list of VLIR-UOS as of June 2016, because of the growing interest for academic cooperation with Cambodia. Currently, there are no ongoing or selected interventions, as Cambodia was not on the VLIR-UOS partner country list and hasn’t been included in calls for proposals since 2013. During the 2017-2021 period, a VLIR-UOS country strategy for Cambodia will be elaborated as to have a reference framework for future interventions. This will be done through consultations in both Belgium and Cambodia which will lead to the identification of priority themes, partners and regions. VLIR-UOS supports interventions that empower higher education institutes in their role as drivers of change by strengthening their threefold mission of research, education and extension to society. For now, the Joint Context Analysis and the Joint Strategic Framework of Cambodia will serve as the guiding framework, so the themes of the interventions will be in line with the domains of the JSF: agriculture/water/food security/rural development, health/access to health, justice and human rights, education/training/research, environment and social economy. The VLIR-UOS programme for Cambodia will be limited to short-term interventions on the individual (scholarships) and departmental level (theme-based capacity building for 2-5 years: TEAM/SI), as a kind of exploratory phase for further broader interventions in the long term after building up experience.

After nearly 20 years of successful cooperation, Cuba assured itself a special place in the VLIR-UOS portfolio as one of top countries. Cuba will have the 2nd highest indicative country budget in the FYP. VLIR-UOS supports interventions that strengthen higher education, research and extension in various domains and with partners in different regions of the country. All interventions frame within the VLIR-UOS Country Strategy for Cuba which is completely aligned with national development and higher education priorities. The strategy is translated into the following main themes: Food security & agricultural production, Environment, Socio-cultural and tourism development (incl. role of cultural heritage), Public health, ICT for development. The prioritised transversal themes are: ICT support and applications (incl. statistics for research and information management); Language (English) and communications; internationalisation, institutional strengthening and human resources and capacity building, doctoral programmes and research and innovation. The core of the 2017-2021 programme will be a long term IUC programme with Universidad de Oriente (Santiago de Cuba) focussing on the development of the Eastern region of Cuba and a national ICT for Development Network programme led by Universidad Central "Marta Abreu" de las Villas. Also 6 TEAM projects and 1 South Initiative projects are foreseen to start as of 2017. A number of new projects (TEAM, SI and JOINT) for Cuba will still be selected in the 2017-2021 period.

A selected number of long-term Institutional University Cooperation (IUC) partnerships between a university in a partner country and Flemish universities and university colleges are supported. The specific objective is to strengthen partner universities’ capacity hereby improving their institutional performance in their threefold mission (education, research and service delivery); and enabling them as driver of change for sustainable development.
The project strategy focuses on:
•	enabling a change process within the partner university leading to improved institutional performance via transversal institutional strengthening sub-projects 
•	strengthening educational and research capacities -through different academic-theme based sub-projects- contributing to developmental change at level of the project region/country of the partner university

BSS strengthens connections within and beyond the VLIR-UOS community through exchange platforms, networks and platform-initiated projects or events in view of collective learning and of facilitating multi-stakeholder partnerships with academics, public, private and civil society actors, hereby improving access and use of academic expertise; and providing scientific (policy) support to enhance the capacity of the Belgian government and other actors in the field of sustainable development.

After more than 15 years of successful cooperation, Ethiopia assured itself a special, top place in the VLIR-UOS portfolio. VLIR-UOS supports interventions that strengthen higher education, research and extension in various domains and with partners in different regions of the country. All interventions frame within the VLIR-UOS Country Strategy for Ethiopia which fits in the Ethiopian national development and higher education priorities. The strategy is translated into the following main themes: 'Food security and agriculture'; 'Environment and water'; 'Economic and social development' and 'Health'. The transversal support themes are 'Governance, institutional strengthening and management'; 'Information management and ICT' and 'Gender and diversity'. The core of the 2017-2021 programme is a national-level institutional Network programme – of 4 Ethiopian public universities, led by Jimma University – dealing with health sector and higher education development and 2 new institutional cooperation programmes (with Arba Minch University and Bahir Dar University). The programme with Arba Minch focuses on sustainable development in the South Ethiopian Rift Valley, while the programme with Bahir Dar puts climate resilient green economy research in northwest central Ethiopia. Furthermore also a Phase Out programme has started for the former IUC with Jimma University. A number of new projects (TEAM, SI and JOINT) for Ethiopia will still be selected in the 2017-2021 period.

Depuis 2010, le VLIR-UOS a un programme de coopération universitaire institutionnelle (CUI), qui est actuellement dans sa deuxième phase et englobe 5 domaines thématiques (sciences de base, santé rurale, sécurité alimentaire, état de droit et TIC et biblio-thèques). La plupart des projets sont basés sur le campus, mais deux d'entre eux opèrent (dans toute la mesure du possible) dans les provinces. Le partenaire doit être renforcé dans son rôle d'acteur du développement par le biais d'interventions en appui de l'enseignement supérieur et de la recherche. En 2013, le VLIR-UOS a défini une stratégie pays qui est en ligne avec le Cadre stratégique de lutte contre la pauvreté (CSLP) adopté par le Burundi et qui sert de cadre de référence pour les interventions actuelles et futures. Les thèmes stratégiques sont les suivants : sciences de base, santé communautaire rurale, état de droit, sécurité alimentaire et développement rural, TIC et bibliothèques, éducation. Les thèmes transversaux concer-nent la bonne gouvernance, les TIC, la qualité de la recherche et de l'éducation, les écoles doctorales, l'anglais académique, le genre et la diversité (non-discrimination). Le VLIR-UOS partage ces thèmes transversaux avec l'ARES.

Global Minds aims to strengthen and deepen the capacities and knowledge of Flemish universities and university colleges in the area of development. For this end, different institutions select and deploy strategic niches/themes that are relevant to the Belgian development cooperation. This capacity building is necessary to implement effective university cooperation for development with other stakeholders, and hence to contribute to facing development challenges in the South.

5 Flemish universities and 13 Flemish university colleges (organised in the consortium of the Vlaamse Hogescholenraad), representing a diverse community (in terms of gender, scientific discipline, nationality and stage of the academic career) of staff, students and alumni.
